A lot of people, 29 million,
still have no
insurance.

10:44.577 --> 10:48.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For those who are on Obamacare
exchanges,
premiums, out-of-pocket costs,
they are rising.

10:48.781 --> 10:52.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And their choices are shrinking.

10:52.218 --> 10:57.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Forecasts estimate that in a
third of all
U.S. counties, the exchange will
offer just

10:57.357 --> 11:00.026 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a single insurer to choose from.

11:00.059 --> 11:05.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for Americans, a day of
historic bright
news, but after climbing out of
a long recession

11:05.932 --> 11:11.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and while grappling with still
unsolved issues
like income inequality, they may
not feel

11:11.404 --> 11:13.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the sunshine yet.

11:13.239 --> 11:16.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lisa
Desjardins.

11:16.176 --> 11:21.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Recently, Hillary
Clinton has
been criticized for allegedly
giving special

11:21.714 --> 11:26.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
access to Clinton Foundation
donors when she
served as secretary of state.

11:27.020 --> 11:31.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now Donald Trump is catching
heat for
how his foundation has
functioned.

11:31.624 --> 11:36.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm joined by David Fahrenthold
of The Washington
Post, who has spent the past few
months digging

11:36.229 --> 11:43.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into the Republican nominee's
history of charitable
donations and his lack of
personal contributions

11:43.169 --> 11:45.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the Trump Foundation.

11:45.204 --> 11:47.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Fahrenthold, thank you for
talking with
us.

11:47.740 --> 11:50.043 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tell us first a little bit about
the foundation.

11:50.076 --> 11:51.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How is it set up?

11:51.344 --> 11:53.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How is it different from other
foundations?

11:53.146 --> 11:55.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD, The
Washington Post: Well,
it's quite a small foundation.

11:55.214 --> 11:57.083 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Trump started it in 1987.

11:57.116 --> 12:00.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in contrast to other people
who have about
as much money as Trump has, it
doesn't have

12:00.787 --> 12:01.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very much money in at all.

12:02.021 --> 12:06.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The most money it ever had was
about $3.3
million in 2009.

12:06.125 --> 12:08.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The most money it has now is
about $1 million
total.

12:08.962 --> 12:11.631 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, there's no paid staff.

12:11.664 --> 12:16.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The board of it is just four
Trumps, Donald,
Donald Jr., Eric, and Ivanka,
and one Trump

12:16.970 --> 12:18.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Organization employee.

12:18.137 --> 12:19.539 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They all work with no pay.

12:19.572 --> 12:21.474 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They work half-an-hour a week.

12:21.507 --> 12:26.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The most unusual thing about it
is not just
that it's small, but whose money
is in it.

12:26.045 --> 12:29.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump hasn't put any
money into his
own foundation until 2008.

12:29.148 --> 12:30.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Instead, he's got other people
to donate.

12:31.017 --> 12:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then he sort of gives their
money to away
to people who under the
impression that they're

12:34.554 --> 12:36.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
getting Donald Trump's money.

12:36.322 --> 12:40.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, when you say
other people
have put money in, what sort of
people are

12:40.126 --> 12:41.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we talking about?

12:41.427 --> 12:43.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD: Well, a lot
of them don't
want to talk.

12:43.196 --> 12:47.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the biggest donation you can
see in tax
filings is from Vince and Linda
McMahon, the

12:47.333 --> 12:49.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WWE moguls.

12:49.302 --> 12:51.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump was on WrestleMania in
2007.

12:51.037 --> 12:55.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in that year and 2009, the
McMahons gave
a total of $5 million.

12:55.441 --> 12:57.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, we know that wasn't Trump's
payment for
WrestleMania.

12:57.844 --> 13:02.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He got paid separately, but
about the same
time, they made this $5 million
donation.

13:02.281 --> 13:06.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other biggest donor has been
this guy
Richard Ebers, who is a sort of
high-end ticket

13:06.819 --> 13:09.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
broker, like tickets to events,
in New York
City.

13:09.122 --> 13:14.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He gives every year between
$450,000 and $600,000,
always in very odd amounts.

13:14.293 --> 13:15.728 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's never an even amount.

13:15.762 --> 13:19.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He also didn't want to talk
about why he gives
to the Trump Foundation.

13:19.499 --> 13:23.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the thing big gifts
has been from
NBC Universal, which televised
"Celebrity

13:23.703 --> 13:25.471 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Apprentice."

13:25.505 --> 13:28.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump often used his Trump
Foundation money
to give what he said were
personal gifts out

13:28.741 --> 13:30.510 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of his own pocket on the show.

13:30.543 --> 13:34.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NBC gave him a $500,000 gift,
which served
to cover the cost of all of
those -- quote,

13:34.781 --> 13:36.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
unquote -- "personal donations."

13:36.282 --> 13:39.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, what about
what the foundation
has given money to?

13:39.318 --> 13:43.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is there a pattern, is there a
mission, a
particular cause that Donald
Trump has been

13:44.023 --> 13:45.224 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
interested in?

13:45.258 --> 13:47.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD: Well, that's
really interesting
as well.

13:47.093 --> 13:49.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of times, you see rich
people who start
their own private foundations,
they are -- as

13:49.862 --> 13:51.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you said, there is an abiding
cause.

13:51.698 --> 13:54.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They give to their alma mater,
they give to
cancer research, they give to
something like

13:54.233 --> 13:55.401 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

13:55.435 --> 13:57.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With Trump, there is no such
abiding cause
like that.

13:57.370 --> 14:01.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's always -- the money is
given out in relatively
small amounts, between $5,000
and $50,000,

14:01.107 --> 14:03.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it's to a smattering of
groups.

14:03.342 --> 14:06.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Often, he's buying a table at a
gala or something
like that.

14:06.379 --> 14:11.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The biggest correlation you find
is with Trump's
own personal and business
interests.

14:11.417 --> 14:15.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He lives in Palm Beach part of
the year, where
charity galas are a big part of
the life.

14:15.254 --> 14:19.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he runs a club in Palm
Beach, Mar-a-Lago,
that depends a lot on being
rented out by

14:19.959 --> 14:24.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
charities, who can pay as much
as $275,000
per night to rent out his club.

14:24.564 --> 14:27.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So he gives to those charities
that do business
with him.

14:27.100 --> 14:30.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this enables him to sort of
give to those
groups without actually using
his own money.

14:30.670 --> 14:36.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You have also --
you also wrote,
David Fahrenthold, that the
Trump Foundation

14:36.542 --> 14:42.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at least in once instance,
actually in several
instances, to political causes
or political

14:42.582 --> 14:43.716 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
candidates.

14:43.750 --> 14:45.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD: Well, there's
one case
in particular.

14:45.418 --> 14:48.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, giving to a political group
is against
the law.

14:48.254 --> 14:50.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're a nonprofit, you can't
give money
to a political group.

14:50.690 --> 14:52.558 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And in 2013, they did that.

14:52.592 --> 14:56.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They gave to this group called
And Justice
for All, which was a political
campaign committee

14:56.596 --> 15:00.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
helping Florida Attorney General
Pam Bondi,
who at the time just happened to
be considering,

15:00.833 --> 15:04.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her office was considering,
whether to pursue
an investigation against Trump
University.

15:04.437 --> 15:08.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They later on, after the money
came in, decided
not to pursue that
investigation.

15:08.641 --> 15:12.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump paid that money out of the
Trump Foundation,
which is against the law.

15:12.612 --> 15:17.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this year, after we pointed
it out, he
paid a penalty tax to the IRS of
$2,500, which

15:17.083 --> 15:18.885 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was 10 percent of the donation.

15:18.918 --> 15:22.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So they're not
under any legal
cloud at this point?

15:22.588 --> 15:26.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD: Well, what's
interesting
is, there is another side to
that gift, which

15:26.259 --> 15:30.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is, not only did Trump's
foundation make that
prohibited political gift, but
they also sent

15:30.763 --> 15:35.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
filing to the IRS which
contained an error
that served to cover up the
illegal gift that

15:35.468 --> 15:37.270 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they made.

15:37.303 --> 15:39.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, they said that error was
inadvertent,
but it was a great coincidence
that the same

15:39.372 --> 15:43.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year they made a $25,000 gift to
this group
they shouldn't have, they told
the IRS they

15:43.342 --> 15:46.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had given $25,000 to another
group, which
would have been legal if they
had actually

15:46.913 --> 15:47.880 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sent them any money.

15:47.914 --> 15:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's something the IRS could
investigate.

15:49.749 --> 15:51.584 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We don't know if it actually is.

15:51.617 --> 15:55.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, we have to
point out that
the Trump campaign, Mr. Trump
himself, says

15:55.855 --> 16:00.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
he's actually given away
millions of dollars
over the years.

16:01.027 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do we know about that in
any form?

16:03.563 --> 16:05.331 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID FAHRENTHOLD: You're right.

16:05.364 --> 16:09.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's said over the years that
he's given the
proceeds of a variety of things,
books, TV

16:09.602 --> 16:11.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shows, to charity, and it adds
up to millions
of dollars.

16:11.971 --> 16:13.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He said he gives millions of
dollars.

16:13.806 --> 16:16.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what I have done over the
last few months
is go looking for evidence that
those gifts

16:16.342 --> 16:17.310 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exist.

16:17.343 --> 16:18.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm not trying the find all of
them.

16:18.678 --> 16:19.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm just trying to find some
evidence that
they're out there.

16:20.012 --> 16:22.348 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, so far, I have called 326
charities.

16:22.381 --> 16:26.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, these are charities that
seem closest
to Trump, people he's given
Trump Foundation

16:26.385 --> 16:30.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
