years of college
tomorrow.

34:28.366 --> 34:32.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN LOPEZ, Project MALES: The
series is called
Rethinking College, and it's
part of our weekly

34:32.604 --> 34:35.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
education coverage, Making the
grade.

34:35.340 --> 34:39.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: If I can have the mentors
on one side
and the mentees on another.

34:39.644 --> 34:44.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Graduate
student Juan Lopez
wants to bring to college
campuses what he

34:44.049 --> 34:47.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sees as largely missing, Latino
males.

34:47.118 --> 34:52.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN LOPEZ: They're not seen as
people who
will succeed, especially
minority males of

34:52.557 --> 34:53.525 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
color.

34:53.558 --> 34:55.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I want to go to college.

34:55.393 --> 34:58.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, on this
day, Lopez and
undergraduates from the
university of Texas

34:58.496 --> 35:03.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at Austin are mentoring high
school freshman
boys as part of an initiative
called Project

35:03.735 --> 35:04.936 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MALES.

35:04.970 --> 35:07.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUAN LOPEZ: Undergraduates
mentor high school
students.

35:07.472 --> 35:10.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Graduate students mentor
undergraduate students.

35:10.742 --> 35:16.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In this
exercise, college
and high school students move
together over

35:16.748 --> 35:18.483 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shared experiences.

35:18.516 --> 35:22.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN LOPEZ: MD+IT /MD-IT /I want
to help
my family out financially after
I graduate

35:22.354 --> 35:23.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
high school.

35:23.888 --> 35:27.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One common
concern emerges
for both mentors and mentees.

35:27.325 --> 35:30.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMMET CAMPOS, Director, Project
MALES: They're
expected to be the wage earner
in the family.

35:30.862 --> 35:34.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Emmet Campos
directs Project
MALES' school mentoring
programs.

35:34.265 --> 35:37.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
EMMET CAMPOS: So, their
expectations that
they get from their family and
from their

35:37.836 --> 35:42.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
peers is that their goal is to
get a job,
and to earn an income.

35:42.707 --> 35:47.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so those factors are pulling
them away
from actually going to college.

35:47.078 --> 35:51.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Pablo Hall is
a high school
sophomore and the oldest boy in
his family.

35:51.583 --> 35:53.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PABLO HALL, High School Student:
I want to
make money after high school, so
that when

35:53.318 --> 35:57.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my mom gets older, I can put her
in a house,
and my brothers, like, keep them
good.

35:57.722 --> 36:01.192 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I just want to help my family
after high school.

36:01.226 --> 36:06.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Even when
students get to
college, financial obligations
can continue

36:06.731 --> 36:08.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to haunt them.

36:08.533 --> 36:10.635 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANTONIO SALMERO, College
Student: When I was
doing the two job thing, it was
really hard,

36:10.669 --> 36:16.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and everybody was excelling on
their tests
and their homework and their
projects, and

36:16.274 --> 36:17.642 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I was starting to fall behind.

36:17.675 --> 36:20.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Antonio
Salmero is a senior
at U.T. Austin.

36:20.779 --> 36:25.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTONIO SALMERO: I felt really
discouraged
even to be in college, but, yes,
the reason

36:25.216 --> 36:29.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
why, because someone's got to
pay bills, somebody
has got to help out at home.

36:29.788 --> 36:33.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of these kids in some of my
classes,
I know, haven't even worked a
day in their

36:33.191 --> 36:34.225 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

36:34.259 --> 36:37.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, that's always very stressful
and discouraging.

36:37.495 --> 36:42.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN LOPEZ: Our parents are
accustomed to
the traditions of Mexico, of
Latin America,

36:43.001 --> 36:45.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
El Salvador, Guatemala, et
cetera.

36:45.970 --> 36:48.540 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And over there, you got to work.

36:48.573 --> 36:51.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What puts food on the table is
work.

36:51.309 --> 36:58.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's this kind of mental
setback that
is instilled in our Latino males
that makes

36:58.750 --> 37:03.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them have to choose between an
education and
a job.

37:03.388 --> 37:09.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTONIO SALMERO: Growing up,
there was always
this cultural belief that a
man's worth is

37:09.761 --> 37:11.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
defined by his work.

37:11.429 --> 37:14.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's this sense of machismo
in the Mexican
culture.

37:14.332 --> 37:19.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And machismo is the belief that
being a man
is providing for your family.

37:19.170 --> 37:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In the U.S.,
one in four
children are Latino.

37:23.174 --> 37:28.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economists project that, within
four years,
two-thirds of all jobs will
require post-secondary

37:28.780 --> 37:31.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
education and training beyond
high school.

37:31.516 --> 37:35.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Victor Saenz, professor at the
University
of Texas, Austin, founded the
Project MALES

37:35.687 --> 37:37.555 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
initiative.

37:37.589 --> 37:39.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICTOR SAENZ, Project MALES: The
demographic
reality of this country and the
future population

37:40.024 --> 37:45.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
projections suggests that the
current 55 million
Hispanics in this country is
poised to double

37:45.630 --> 37:47.398 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the next 40 to 50 years.

37:47.432 --> 37:52.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think our future economic
prosperity is
absolutely linked to the
educational outcomes

37:52.036 --> 37:53.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for Latino males.

37:53.805 --> 37:56.941 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: While
Hispanics are the
largest and fastest growing
minority in the

37:56.975 --> 38:01.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country, they have lowest
educational attainment
of any group.

38:01.579 --> 38:08.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The high school graduation rate
for Latinos
is 71 percent, but only 15
percent of Latinos

38:08.052 --> 38:09.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
hold bachelor's degrees.

38:09.988 --> 38:15.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And despite significant
increases in college
enrollment among Hispanics, a
troubling trend

38:15.360 --> 38:16.794 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has emerged.

38:16.828 --> 38:19.130 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Latino men lag far behind women.

38:19.164 --> 38:23.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICTOR SAENZ: The men of color
conversation
nationally has really taken root
and has gained

38:24.002 --> 38:25.470 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
great momentum.

38:25.503 --> 38:29.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Project MALES is rooted in this
larger social
justice agenda.

38:29.374 --> 38:34.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Project MALES
explores the
reasons why so many Latino boys
stop short

38:34.646 --> 38:36.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of four-year degrees.

38:36.314 --> 38:40.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICTOR SAENZ: We see that Latino
boys are
over-represented in the special
education

38:40.051 --> 38:42.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ranks, over-represented in the
school discipline
pipeline.

38:42.453 --> 38:46.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And by the time they get to high
school and
college, their numbers have
dwindled to the

38:46.224 --> 38:50.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
point where there's not enough
of them to
really look at student
populations.

38:50.328 --> 38:55.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Austin High
School principal
Ty Davidson says mentors are
especially important

38:55.967 --> 38:58.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for first-generation students
considering
college.

38:58.536 --> 39:02.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TY DAVIDSON, Principal, Austin
High School:
There's somebody there who looks
like you,

39:02.640 --> 39:07.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
may have the same experience as
you, about
anxiety over financial aid, the
anxiety of

39:07.645 --> 39:10.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
maybe moving away from home,
saying, it's
going to be OK.

39:10.648 --> 39:12.750 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's, we're going to do it
together.

39:12.784 --> 39:17.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Project MALES
mentors spend
a lot of time talking to young
men about the

39:17.288 --> 39:20.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
economic realities of being an
unskilled worker.

39:20.291 --> 39:22.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EMMET CAMPOS: We show them the
data.

39:22.126 --> 39:26.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We provide them with information
about degrees
and how they translate into
incomes, into

39:26.130 --> 39:27.665 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
salaries.

39:27.699 --> 39:31.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: At Gus Garcia
Middle School,
mentors talk dollars and cents.

39:31.069 --> 39:36.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: So, I just wanted to ask
you all if any
of you all have an idea of how
much the minimum

39:36.040 --> 39:37.108 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
wage is right now?

39:37.141 --> 39:38.109 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Twelve.

39:38.142 --> 39:39.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Twelve dollars an hour?

39:39.244 --> 39:40.211 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STUDENT: Fifteen.

39:40.245 --> 39:41.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Fifteen an hour?

39:41.246 --> 39:42.213 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Ten.

39:42.247 --> 39:43.548 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Ten dollars an hour?

39:43.581 --> 39:47.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I guess minimum wage is
probably a little
over $14,000.

39:47.051 --> 39:49.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Does that sound like a lot of
money?

39:49.354 --> 39:52.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STUDENT: No, $14,000 is barely
enough to buy
a car.

39:52.290 --> 39:53.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: You think you could live
off of that?

39:53.992 --> 39:55.627 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: No.

39:55.660 --> 39:57.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMMET CAMPOS: We talk about,
have you thought
of what that car's going to
cost?

39:57.295 --> 39:59.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Have you thought about what that
house is
going to cost?

39:59.364 --> 40:03.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PABLO HALL: There are times when
I felt I
want to drop out of school.

40:03.101 --> 40:07.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Pablo Hall,
who was thinking
of dropping out of high school
as a freshman,

40:07.705 --> 40:09.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
says Project MALES has made a
difference.

40:09.941 --> 40:12.076 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PABLO HALL: The mentors, they're
good.

40:12.110 --> 40:14.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When I need help, they help me
with it.

40:14.145 --> 40:16.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can tell the mentors what's
going on.

40:16.414 --> 40:20.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: At the same
time, Antonio
Salmero says mentoring high
school students

40:20.585 --> 40:23.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
helped him when he thought of
leaving college.

40:23.488 --> 40:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:66.67% size:100%
ANTONIO SALMERO: I mean, I see
myself pushing
this idea of
self-responsibility, of
self-reliance,

40:30.628 --> 40:35.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and determination onto myself,
much like I
do want to make them realize
that as well.

40:35.400 --> 40:39.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The program
hopes some of
its graduate students will
return to college

40:39.404 --> 40:44.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campus as professors, a career
also largely
underrepresented by Latino men.

40:45.009 --> 40:52.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm Hari Sreenivasan for the
"PBS NewsHour."

40:52.283 --> 41:06.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Next: an
award-winning novelist
and bookseller draws on her own
life story

41:06.130 --> 41:08.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for her latest tale.

41:08.266 --> 41:13.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown takes the
"NewsHour" Bookshelf
to Nashville to visit with
writer Ann Patchett.

41:13.838 --> 41:21.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: At the East
Nashville Farmers
Market recently, you could
listen to music,

41:21.379 --> 41:28.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down a cool drink, buy some
vegetables, and,
why not, grab yourself a new
book to read.

41:28.686 --> 41:30.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT, Author,
"Commonwealth": This
is where the people are.

41:30.355 --> 41:34.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can get a squash and a book,
a tomato
and a book.

41:34.325 --> 41:36.127 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's great.

41:36.160 --> 41:39.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You could also
meet a famous
local writer, Ann Patchett, who,
since 2011,

41:39.964 --> 41:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is co-owner of Nashville's
Parnassus Books
and its traveling bookmobile.

41:44.435 --> 41:47.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: So, we got a
little bit of everything.

41:47.572 --> 41:49.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lots of kids books, lots of
kids.

41:49.173 --> 41:50.141 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Kids love the bus.

41:50.174 --> 41:51.943 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Kids love the
bus.

41:51.976 --> 41:56.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Kids cannot get
enough of the
bus, so the books that are down
low, those

41:56.414 --> 41:58.216 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are always really important.

41:58.249 --> 42:01.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You don't even
need, like,
kids' toys or anything to
attract them, huh?

42:01.686 --> 42:02.987 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: No, no, no bait.

42:03.020 --> 42:03.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Books are the bait.

42:04.021 --> 42:05.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's our message.

42:05.056 --> 42:06.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Books are the
bait.

42:06.924 --> 42:08.393 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

42:08.426 --> 42:11.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The 52-year-old
bookseller
is herself a bestselling author.

42:11.763 --> 42:17.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her novels include the 2001 "Bel
Canto" about
an opera singer taken hostage in
a terror

42:17.635 --> 42:23.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack in an unnamed Latin
American country,
and 2011's "State of Wonder,"
centered on

42:23.641 --> 42:27.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pharmaceutical drug research in
the Amazon.

42:27.044 --> 42:32.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now she's done something closer
to home, writing
a novel about a family much like
the one she

42:32.116 --> 42:38.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
herself grew up in, two
families, in fact,
blended together after a chance
encounter

42:38.222 --> 42:40.725 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
leads to infidelity and divorce.

42:40.758 --> 42:45.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her new novel, "Commonwealth,"
follows four
adults and six children through
50 years of

42:45.630 --> 42:47.131 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ups and downs.

42:47.165 --> 42:50.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We spoke in her Nashville home,
not too far
from where she grew up.

42:50.802 --> 42:53.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: This is a story
that's very
close to home.

42:53.237 --> 42:56.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a story that is very
close to my life
and my family and...

42:56.607 --> 42:57.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: It is?

42:57.608 --> 42:58.576 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: It is.

42:58.609 --> 42:59.577 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I wasn't sure.

42:59.610 --> 43:00.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: It is.

43:00.611 --> 43:01.579 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, tell me,
how is it?

43:01.612 --> 43:03.347 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
In what ways is it close?

43:03.381 --> 43:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: I was one of two
girls, and
my mother left my father and
married someone

43:09.153 --> 43:11.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who had two boys and two girls.

43:11.322 --> 43:13.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they moved to the other side
of the country.

43:13.391 --> 43:16.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this blended
family, geographically
spread out.

43:16.961 --> 43:17.929 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes, exactly.

43:17.962 --> 43:18.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Parents in
different places.

43:18.963 --> 43:19.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Exactly.

43:19.964 --> 43:21.599 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

43:21.632 --> 43:26.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I really talked to everyone
in my family
while I was working on this
book.

43:26.471 --> 43:27.438 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is this OK with you?

43:27.472 --> 43:28.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do you feel about this?

43:28.739 --> 43:31.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
When I finished, I gave
everybody a copy of
the manuscript.

43:31.209 --> 43:32.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Really?

43:32.210 --> 43:33.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: We talked about
it.

43:33.211 --> 43:34.612 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

43:34.645 --> 43:37.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Because you were
nervous about
how they would take it?

43:37.615 --> 43:38.583 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Or...

43:38.616 --> 43:40.651 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Because I love and
respect them.

43:40.685 --> 43:42.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's their life too.

43:42.753 --> 43:46.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have always been so
careful to not write
this story.

43:47.024 --> 43:49.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have always written "Bel
Canto" instead.

43:50.027 --> 43:55.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when I wanted to write about
someone ripped
out of one family and put into
another family,

43:55.299 --> 43:57.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I put them in Peru.

43:57.969 --> 44:03.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I just said to everybody --
at this point,
I was probably 49 when I started
the book.

44:03.941 --> 44:09.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I said, I want to have
access to my life,
which also means having access
to your life.

44:09.514 --> 44:11.115 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And are you OK with this?

44:11.148 --> 44:14.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this was a
completely different
writing experience for you.

44:14.118 --> 44:15.620 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Totally, totally.

44:15.653 --> 44:18.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is the book that I should
have written
when I was 25, instead of 52.

44:18.923 --> 44:21.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of the
themes, obviously,
is chance, right...

44:21.559 --> 44:22.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes.

44:22.927 --> 44:24.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: ... is how one
thing leads
to just everything.

44:24.962 --> 44:26.764 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Right.

44:26.797 --> 44:32.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't believe in fate, as in,
which I -- as
a Catholic, I think, sort of
predestination.

44:32.503 --> 44:34.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I certainly believe in
chance.

44:34.338 --> 44:37.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I do think -- don't you ever
think that?

44:37.408 --> 44:41.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, if I had turned right this
morning,
instead of left, maybe
everything would have

44:41.078 --> 44:42.046 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
been different?

44:42.079 --> 44:43.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

44:43.080 --> 44:44.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I think we all do.

44:44.649 --> 44:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes, you know, you
miss the
train, but then you meet the
person.

44:47.451 --> 44:49.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that that's --
that's what the
book is about.

44:49.654 --> 44:51.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, everybody believes in
chance.

44:51.756 --> 44:53.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there's a lot of chance in
this book.

44:53.891 --> 44:59.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: But, as a
novelist, that gave
you a way into, sees what
happens?

44:59.730 --> 45:04.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Did you know where it was ending
up, or did
you start all this chance
happening and then

45:04.168 --> 45:05.303 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
see where it might lead?

45:05.336 --> 45:06.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: No, I always know
where it's
ending up.

45:06.604 --> 45:07.572 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: You do?

45:07.605 --> 45:08.739 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: That's the way I
work.

45:08.773 --> 45:13.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I get it all plotted in my mind,
and then
I write it down.

45:13.210 --> 45:16.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, sometimes, things change
a little
bit.

45:16.380 --> 45:19.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I always say it's like
taking a trip.

45:19.283 --> 45:21.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I know where I'm going.

45:21.752 --> 45:24.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if I don't know where I'm
going, I don't
tend to get anywhere.

45:24.789 --> 45:28.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Another theme in
this book
is time, right, the passage of
time.

45:28.893 --> 45:29.860 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes.

45:29.894 --> 45:31.228 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

45:31.262 --> 45:32.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This book starts out with six
kids, and they're
not great kids.

45:32.830 --> 45:34.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have had a lot of upheaval
in their life.

45:34.932 --> 45:36.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're irritating.

45:36.701 --> 45:41.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then you see them in their
20s, their
30s, their 40s, their 50s, and
they grow on

45:41.706 --> 45:42.673 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

45:42.707 --> 45:43.674 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They grow into themselves.

45:43.708 --> 45:45.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They become the people they're
meant to be.

45:45.343 --> 45:48.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I liked the idea of having
enough time
to really see that.

45:48.179 --> 45:52.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: They're also
children who we
see who are kind of --
emotionally, they're

45:52.416 --> 45:53.417 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
just kind of left on their own.

45:53.451 --> 45:54.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes.

45:54.885 --> 45:57.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have had a lot of people
say, oh, these
are terrible parents.

45:57.555 --> 45:59.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I'm like, they're not
terrible parents.

45:59.290 --> 46:00.257 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was the '60s.

46:00.291 --> 46:01.258 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was the '70s.

46:01.292 --> 46:02.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:02.293 --> 46:03.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: I mean, my
parents...

46:03.361 --> 46:04.328 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Go play outside,
right?

46:04.362 --> 46:05.329 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes, exactly.

46:05.363 --> 46:06.330 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Dig a hole.

46:06.364 --> 46:07.598 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And when you're done, fill it up
again.

46:07.632 --> 46:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I actually think that's
really important
for creativity.

46:09.533 --> 46:16.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, if you want to grow a
novelist, for
that person to have a lot of
boring time trying

46:16.173 --> 46:18.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to entertain themselves is very
important.

46:18.609 --> 46:23.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Her partnership
in Parnassus
Books came after Patchett saw
Nashville losing

46:23.614 --> 46:28.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the last of its independent
bookstores and
decided she had no choice but to
enter the

46:28.185 --> 46:29.153 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
retail business.

46:29.186 --> 46:30.888 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: I had no idea.

46:30.921 --> 46:32.923 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I really thought that I was
going a good deed.

46:32.957 --> 46:37.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I thought it was like, the
symphony is going
under, I must save the symphony,
that kind

46:37.395 --> 46:38.362 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of thing.

46:38.396 --> 46:40.965 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I actually really love this
store.

46:40.998 --> 46:42.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I love being here.

46:42.199 --> 46:44.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I love telling people what to
read.

46:44.235 --> 46:49.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's my favorite thing in the
world, to buy
books and force books on people,
take bad

46:49.073 --> 46:51.275 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
books away from people, give
them better books.

46:51.308 --> 46:56.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You opened this
around the
time when the whole narrative of
bookstores

46:56.547 --> 46:57.682 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was, they're going away.

46:57.715 --> 46:59.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes.

46:59.083 --> 47:00.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The narratives of
books, in
fact, were going away.

47:00.584 --> 47:01.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANN PATCHETT: Yes.

47:01.585 --> 47:03.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So what's the
story now?

47:03.821 --> 47:08.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Independent
booksellers, independent
bookstores are on the rise
across the country.

47:08.693 --> 47:10.528 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The ones who've
survived.

47:10.561 --> 47:13.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: The ones who've
survived, but,
actually, a lot of new ones have
started since

47:13.798 --> 47:15.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we opened this store.

47:15.166 --> 47:19.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think that it had bottomed
out, and
then it was going up.

47:19.203 --> 47:21.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the other thing is, this is
my hometown.

47:21.272 --> 47:22.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I knew Nashville.

47:22.606 --> 47:26.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I knew that they loved the
bookstore that
they lost.

47:26.210 --> 47:28.879 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And Nashville supports
everything local.

47:28.913 --> 47:33.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They would always rather buy
their coffee
at Fido than at Starbucks.

47:33.651 --> 47:38.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so this was a city that was
going to support
and independent bookstore.

47:38.222 --> 47:39.957 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And it has.

47:39.990 --> 47:41.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And why do you
think the bookstores
are coming back across the
country?

47:41.992 --> 47:48.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN PATCHETT: Because you can't
spend your
whole life in front of a screen.

47:48.632 --> 47:52.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can't take your family
to anthropology
after dinner.

47:52.636 --> 47:56.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You need someplace to go and
hang out.

47:56.440 --> 47:58.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Everybody can come here.

47:58.509 --> 48:01.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can come here if you're
lonely and you
want to talk to other people who
loves books.

48:01.912 --> 48:05.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you can come here if you're
overwhelmed
and want to be silent and sit
down in a chair

48:05.750 --> 48:09.019 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and read a book.

48:09.053 --> 48:13.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can bring your kid here for
story time.

48:13.157 --> 48:16.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can come here to listen to
your favorite
author.

48:16.227 --> 48:17.862 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, it's a community center.

48:17.895 --> 48:21.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can come here, spend time
here, not buy
a book here.

48:21.432 --> 48:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a beautiful place.

48:23.234 --> 48:25.603 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Or you can come here and buy a
book here.

48:25.636 --> 48:26.604 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's good, too.

48:26.637 --> 48:28.472 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We love that.

48:28.506 --> 48:31.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ann Patchett's
latest novel,
"Commonwealth," is now on sale
at her bookstore

48:31.742 --> 48:34.378 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and, we hope, one near you.

48:34.411 --> 48:43.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From Nashville, I'm Jeffrey
Brown for the
"PBS NewsHour."

48:43.087 --> 48:53.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally to our
"NewsHour" Shares,
something that caught our eye
that might be

48:53.097 --> 48:55.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of interest to you, too.

48:55.366 --> 49:01.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Arizona photographer Mike
Olbinski is a storm
chaser whose time-lapse videos
have been used

49:01.272 --> 49:04.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in commercials, documentaries
and even feature
films.

49:04.608 --> 49:08.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE OLBINSKI, Photographer: My
name is Mike
Olbinski.

49:08.112 --> 49:13.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I am a professional storm
and wedding
photographer based out of
Phoenix, Arizona.

49:13.150 --> 49:15.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's kind of kind of a crazy
profession.

49:15.586 --> 49:21.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I got into it mainly because
I have loved
the weather ever since I was a
kid.

49:21.692 --> 49:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it wasn't until, you know,
early 30s that
I started seeing photos of
lightning, and

49:25.863 --> 49:27.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I just started getting
interested in it.

49:27.565 --> 49:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My time-lapses are still frames.

49:29.533 --> 49:34.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So my camera is taking a picture
every second,
every two seconds, every three
seconds, whatever

49:34.939 --> 49:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm out there trying to do, and
then those
get kind of put together into a
video.

49:39.710 --> 49:45.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It kind of goes back to the old
days of animation,
where people used to draw
cartoons on a piece

49:45.216 --> 49:48.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of paper on like a hundred
pages, and then
flip through it, and you would
get this motion

49:48.986 --> 49:49.954 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happening.

49:49.987 --> 49:52.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I kind of have two chase seasons
in a way.

49:52.156 --> 49:56.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I chase out on the Plains in the
spring, and
then I live in Phoenix, so then
I just chase

49:56.460 --> 49:57.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the monsoon all summer.

49:57.461 --> 49:59.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, obviously, it's a lot
easier here.

49:59.263 --> 50:02.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is kind of where I
started, because
all I have to do is just drive
40 miles to

50:02.700 --> 50:07.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get somewhere to shoot a dust
storm, instead
of driving 16 hours to Oklahoma
to shoot a

50:07.404 --> 50:08.839 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
storm that might not happen.

50:08.873 --> 50:11.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the dust storms are
something that
are kind of unique to us.

50:11.742 --> 50:14.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other people get them every now
and then,
but we get them all the time.

50:14.578 --> 50:19.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The lightning out here is just
-- is probably
better than most places, just
because our

50:19.416 --> 50:24.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
storms are really what they call
high-based,
where the bottom of the storms
are really

50:24.221 --> 50:27.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up high, so you see a lot more
of the lightning
hitting the ground.

50:27.424 --> 50:33.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Out on the Plains, these storms
just take
on otherworldly appearances
because they are

50:33.097 --> 50:34.832 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rotating as they go upwards.

50:34.865 --> 50:39.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And a lot of times, that
rotation ends up
turning the storm into looking
like a flying

50:39.737 --> 50:42.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
saucer or the mother ship, as
everybody likes
to say.

50:42.873 --> 50:48.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have seen some pretty amazing
storms over
the course of the last seven or
eight years.

50:48.212 --> 50:51.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first one was the big dust
storm that
hit Phoenix on July 5, 2011.

50:51.548 --> 50:56.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have lived here my whole life,
and I have
never -- I have seen dust storms
all the time,

50:56.820 --> 50:58.088 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but I have never seen one like
this.

50:58.122 --> 51:00.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It just looked like the end of
the world.

51:00.925 --> 51:07.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A couple years later, in 2013,
we were in
Texas, and we were shooting this
storm in

51:07.097 --> 51:10.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
front of a cornfield that had
been chopped
down.

51:10.167 --> 51:14.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then the sun was setting,
and so the whole
sky was orange.

51:14.071 --> 51:15.172 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And this supercell was spinning.

51:15.205 --> 51:17.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was just sucking up dirt off
the ground.

51:17.541 --> 51:22.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I just love this, like, solitude
of being
out there, being with nature,
seeing these

51:22.046 --> 51:26.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
amazing storms, and trying to
get the best
footage and photos that I
possibly can.

51:26.917 --> 51:28.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All I can say is
wow.

51:28.752 --> 51:32.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Those pictures, the
dust storm
picture of Phoenix, amazing.

51:32.656 --> 51:34.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just -- I have
never seen anything
like it.

51:34.325 --> 51:35.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: I wouldn't want to
be behind the
camera.

51:35.993 --> 51:36.961 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

51:36.994 --> 51:38.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
