first woman and the first
African-American

51:55.946 --> 52:00.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to seek the Democratic
nomination.

52:00.884 --> 52:09.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Four thousand blacks, some
radical, some
conservative, met in Gary,
Indiana, for the

52:09.059 --> 52:11.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
first National Black Political
Convention.

52:11.261 --> 52:16.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: A conference was called
in Gary to
discuss black political power.

52:16.600 --> 52:21.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Passage of the '65 Voting Rights
Act enabled
a lot of African-Americans to
believe that

52:21.338 --> 52:27.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they could play a greater role
in national
politics as an organized black
force.

52:27.845 --> 52:32.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When this conference takes
place, Mrs. Chisholm
decides not to go.

52:32.383 --> 52:34.184 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

52:34.218 --> 52:37.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES RANGEL (D), New York:
Listen, when
you have enough political
courage to do what

52:37.821 --> 52:44.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Shirley Chisholm has done, which
I never had
this much of it, I'm not
prepared to give

52:44.395 --> 52:46.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
advice as to what she should
have done.

52:46.730 --> 52:51.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: And Chisholm chose not to
go because,
one, she had already announced
that she was

52:51.368 --> 52:56.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to run for president, and
she didn't
feel like catching flak, and she
didn't want

52:56.273 --> 52:59.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be there when there was a
vote of non-support
for her.

52:59.176 --> 53:05.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: I went to the Gary,
Indiana, Black
Political Convention, and we
tried to get

53:05.182 --> 53:10.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an endorsement from the Black
Political Convention
delegates for Shirley Chisholm
for president.

53:10.654 --> 53:12.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We couldn't even get it there.

53:12.089 --> 53:15.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, the guys had it so sewed
up.

53:15.192 --> 53:22.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: They could not stand the
fact that
a black woman kind of
leapfrogged over them

53:22.132 --> 53:24.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and made the decision for
herself to run.

53:24.835 --> 53:29.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For many, they thought a black
man should
do this first.

53:29.306 --> 53:33.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MELISSA HARRIS-PERRY, Wake
Forest University:
She sees black men as awful
extremely hostile

53:33.143 --> 53:34.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to her candidacy.

53:34.945 --> 53:38.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The bigger part of the joke for
them isn't
that she's an African-American
running, but,

53:38.449 --> 53:40.184 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like, she's a girl running.

53:40.217 --> 53:43.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not going to have some
girl president,
right, much less a black girl
president.

